defaultBeaches.name: Cromwell's Beach
defaultBeaches.description: A hidden gem in Diamond head away from the busy city. A little rocky, but beautiful and relaxing nonetheless.

defaultBeaches.name: Lanikai Beach
defaultBeaches.description: A popular tourist spot known to many. A fantasy beach in hawaii. Clear waters, white sands, and lots of fun!

defaultBeaches.name: Sunset beach
defaultBeaches.description: A famous beach on the north shore. Known for its enormous waves and beautiful sunsets.

defaultBeaches.name: Waimea bay
defaultBeaches.description: A famous beach on the north shore. Known for its enormous waves, beautiful sunsets, and certified spunjahz.

defaultBeaches.name: Sandy Beach
defaultBeaches.description: A nice stretch of beach with a park behind. Obama once surfed these waters but, be careful the waves are known for being dangerous for inexperienced swimmers.

defaultBeaches.name: Makapu'u Beach
defaultBeaches.description: Right across from Sea Life park is a gem of a beach tucked away on the side of the road. Lots of waves and great for boogie boarding and surfing.

defaultBeaches.name: White Plains
defaultBeaches.description: A beach with a beautiful drive through the Ewa region. A great beach for beginner surfers and boogie boarders alike. Also a great spot to have BBQ’s and throw some parties!

defaultBeaches.name: Pokai Bay
defaultBeaches.description: This beach is on the far west side of the island but, you get to experience the beauty of the west side on your way to the beach. Enjoy a beach popular with the locals with friendly faces and big braddahz.

defaultBeaches.name: Chinaman's Hat
defaultBeaches.description: A one of a kind beach! There is an island that looks like a Chinaman’s hat hence the name. Lots of activities to do here like kayaking, hang out on the sand bar, going over to the island, or just having a BBQ with friends.

defaultBeaches.name: Sherwoods Beach
defaultBeaches.description: A beautiful white sand beach with plenty of space to go camping. Waves crash close to the beach making this a great place for boogie boarding or body surfing. Be careful there are jellyfishes that appear from time to time.

defaultBeaches.name: Kawaikui Beach Park
defaultBeaches.description: A great after work beach or Sunday afternoon beach. This beach is very mellow and has plenty of places to just relax listen to the ocean and destress. If you are into surfing this beach is a good spot, though you do have to swim out a good distance.

defaultBeaches.name: Ala Moana Beach Park
defaultBeaches.description: A beach that does it all. Yes, it may be a little crowded. You can do almost everything from BBQs, to surfing, to snorkeling, to parties, to kayaking, and much more.

defaultBeaches.name: Barbers Point Beach
defaultBeaches.description: Another great beach that the west side has to offer. Good waves, good weather, white sand, clear waters, and good people whats not to love about this place.

defaultHikes.name: Lanikai Pill Box
defaultHikes.description: Experience the mountain environment in this beginner level hike. Witness the beautiful view of lanikai beach from atop the pillbox!

defaultHikes.name: Manoa Falls
defaultHikes.description: HIdden deep in the valley of Manoa is a beautiful jungle hike. The best part about the hike is being able to see the wonderful waterfall that rewards the effort to get there

defaultHikes.name: Koko Head
defaultHikes.description: A hike by an unconventional means. To get to the summit of Koko head you have to hike up an old railway track. It’s a rather difficult hike if you’re not into stairs.

defaultHikes.name: Aiea Loop Trail
defaultHikes.description: A fantasy like hike through the mountains in Aiea. Smells of eucalyptus and rainfall bring a calming and relaxing feeling. But becareful it’s a long hike and rains frequently.

defaultHikes.name: Makapu’u Point Lighthouse
defaultHikes.description: One of the nicest and most modern hikes Oahu has to offer. Enjoy a nice paved road all the way up to the old lighthouse. From the top there is a breathtaking view of the eastern side of the island.

defaultHikes.name: Diamond Head
defaultHikes.description: Definitely a tourist attraction spot but for good reason. Breathtaking view with a diverse and adventures hike to go with it. This spot is a bucket list item for sure.

defaultHikes.name: MT. Olympus
defaultHikes.description: To start you have to go to Wa’ahila Ridge state park to follow the trail. Definitely not a hike for beginners. The view you get from being in the center of Oahu looking out to the city is one words can’t describe.

defaultHikes.name: Wiliwilinui
defaultHikes.description: Hiking through the lush green mountains in the center or Oahu. This is a must-see hiking spot for those of you with a little more experience. Don’t forget to always hike with a buddy and be caurfule it can get really muddy here.

defaultHikes.name: Ka'ena Point Trail
defaultHikes.description: Traveling to the furthest region of Oahu here you find an area known as Ka’ena point. A relatively easy hiking trail is here along with great place to just be away from the business of Honolulu and enjoy a little zen.

defaultHikes.name: Crouching Lion
defaultHikes.description: This hike is a bit of a drive to get to but well worth it. If your looking for something with an intermediate difficulty and a view that makes it worth it look no further. Be cautious there are steep sloped and the rain does not help with that.

defaultHikes.name: Pali Puka
defaultHikes.description: After seeing the beautiful sights from Pali lookout you are then able to begin your adventure to Pali Puka. Once completed enjoy beautiful view seen through the puka with a Narnia like feel.

defaultHikes.name: Chinamans Hat Island
defaultHikes.description: A unique hike unlike any other. To do this hike you are going to have to travel to Chinamans hat island either by kayak or walk there if the tide is low. From there you are then abe to have a leisure hike to the top and enjoy the view.

defaultViews.name: Tantalus Lookout
defaultViews.description: One of the most breathtaking views on the island.

defaultViews.name: Tantalus Lookout at Puu Ualakaa
defaultViews.description: Near the Tantalus drive lookout this lookout gives you a different perspective showing more of the west side of the island. The benefit to this place is that it’s a state park so a great place to have a picnic or get together with friends and family.

defaultViews.name: Valley of the Temples
defaultViews.description: A beautiful Japanese inspired scenery all around from the temples to the landscape and ponds. Don’t forget to ring the bell while you are here.

defaultViews.name: Pali Lookout
defaultViews.description: A stunning view from the Pali mountains looking out into Kaneohe. Another tourist spot but, there is history behind this gorgeous view.

defaultViews.name: Lyon Arboretum
defaultViews.description: A magnificent botanical garden right in the back of UH Manoa. Enjoy ally types of flowers, plants, trees, and everything nature like here

defaultViews.name: Waimea Valley
defaultViews.description: If you had to visit a place to get the most bang for your time this would be it. Beautiful nature surrounding, an nice waterfall, a calm pond to swim in, and a botanical garden! What is not to love about this place.

defaultViews.name: Kualoa Ranch
defaultViews.description: Did you know that Jurassic Park was filmed here! Wonderful place with lots of activities to do as well as being able to just enjoy the peacefulness that Kaneohe has to offer.

defaultViews.name: Haleiwa Town Center
defaultViews.description: Taking a trip to the past. This area is like coming back to the simple days with retro looking stores and aesthetics. This may be a more touristy spot but definitely worth the visit.

defaultViews.name: Ho’omaluhia Botanical Garden
defaultViews.description: Ever wanted to take cool looking photos with a beautiful natural background? Well, this is the place to do it. A beautiful garden with so much to see. Don't forget your camera because the views are breathtaking.

defaultViews.name: China Walls
defaultViews.description: Sitting in the back of million dollar homes is a gem of a spot. Find a wonderful view of the east coast here and take some breathtaking photos. If you come at night you can look up at the stars and just get lost in your own thoughts.

defaultSpots.name: Hamilton Library
defaultSpots.location: In the Upper portion of the UH Manoa campus
defaultSpots.description: Great place to study or meet with a team for a meeting.

defaultSpots.name: Japanese Garden
defaultSpots.description: A tranquil spot guaranteed to help calm and relax you when you come to this location. This is a great spot to hangout or meditate at if you are feeling overwhelm or exhausted from school, life, or work.

defaultSpots.name: Warrior Rec Center
defaultSpots.description: Great place to get a quick workout or cardio session between classes. Wide variety of fitness equipment to meet your needs

defaultSpots.name: Paradise Palms Cafe
defaultSpots.description: Hungry? This place offers a variety of foods to eat. Also it double as a great place to study. Located in the center of campus it is a must to stop by this conveniently located area.

defaultSpots.name: Hemenway Courtyard
defaultSpots.description: Enjoy an open top courtyard equipped with table and umbrella at Hemenway courtyard. A nice place to study in the outdoors or relax while you wait for your next class. Also if you get hungry there are lots of great food spot to eat at nearby.

defaultSpots.name: Sinclair Library
defaultSpots.description: A wonderful place to go if you feel like you are having a hard time focusing on your work. A lot of students go to this place to study or do homework. It is a great environment to get in the zone and complete your work.

defaultVolunteer.name: Honolulu Zoo Volunteer
defaultVolunteer.description: Front Entrance Greeters are outgoing, energetic, friendly, well-spoken volunteers who enjoy greeting and sharing interesting facts about the zoo and how guests can best enjoy their time during their visit. They share their passion for the zoo by welcoming visitors and answering and anticipating questions. They assist with ensuring current safety protocols and are the first line of interaction zoo guests receive upon entering the zoo.

defaultVolunteer.name: Meals on Wheels
defaultVolunteer.description: Hawai‘i Meals on Wheels is dedicated to helping Oahu’s elders and individuals with disabilities preserve their independence at home. We do this primarily by providing hot, nutritious meals and regular personal interaction with those we serve

defaultVolunteer.name: 808 Cleanups
defaultVolunteer.description: 808 Cleanups is a 501(c)(3) environmental nonprofit organization committed to restoring Hawaiʻi’s natural beauty by empowering volunteers to conduct decentralized cleanups from Mauka to Makai, responding to littering and vandalism of Hawaiʻi’s natural spaces, saving Hawaiʻi’s indigenous ecosystem through education, and building sustainable solutions with community partners.

defaultVolunteer.name: Sustainable Coastlines Hawaii
defaultVolunteer.description: Inspired by our good friends Sustainable Coastlines in New Zealand, we decided to take keeping our beaches clean into our own hands while making the work fun. What we’ve learned along the way is that cleanups can only do so much. We now utilize our cleanups to inspire better consumer behaviors and continued coastal stewardship through cleanups, education, social media, and more.

defaultVolunteer.name: LBE Hawaii Community Service
defaultVolunteer.description: While community service opportunities are embedded into many of our programs for our learners, LbE Hawaii regularly organizes and participates in dozens of community service events throughout the year.

defaultVolunteer.name: Hawaii Foodbank
defaultVolunteer.description: The people of Hawaii are one ʻohana. Hawaii Foodbank provides food so that no one in our family goes hungry. We work to gather food and support from our communities. We then distribute food through charitable agencies to those in need. Our mission is from the heart, and we will fulfill our mission with integrity, humanity and aloha.

defaultVolunteer.name: AccesSurf Hawaii
defaultVolunteer.description: AccesSurf builds an inclusive community that empowers people with disabilities through accessible beach and water programs

defaultVolunteer.name: Travel2change
defaultVolunteer.description: We all love to travel. But let’s face it—travel can create social and environmental problems. At travel2change we believe that by exploring the world, we can better it. Discover fun and impactful activities offered by local communities. Together we can transform tourism so that local communities benefit.  travel2change is a Hawaii based 501(c)(3) nonprofit organization.

defaultVolunteer.name: Blood Bank of Hawaii
defaultVolunteer.description: We would not be able to meet the needs of Hawaii’s patients without our team of volunteers. Each and every day, volunteers play a critical role in getting blood to patients who need it, and providing support in a variety of ways. Some of the ways you can help: Monitor donors after they have given blood, Provide administrative and clerical support, Help with special projects, Telephone donors to confirm their blood donation appointment, Host our donor refreshment area, If you see an opportunity to help, just ask. Volunteer on a schedule that fits your needs in a fun, friendly environment with caring staff members.
